Gommo,

I am not an expert user of the junit ant task--I hope that someone
else on this list is, and can provide more insight.  You might want to
look at the Johannes&#39; Links ClasspathSuite runner:

http://johanneslink.net/cpsuite.html

Using this, you&#39;d point ant at a single suite class, which would
itself indicate the directory in which to search for tests.  I&#39;ve
found cpsuite remarkably fast for small-to-medium projects, but can&#39;t
say how it scales to large or very large projects.  Thanks,

   David Saff

On 8/19/07, gommo &lt;colin.goudie@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;ve been using TestNG for more unit and integration tests. However, I&#39;ve
&gt; found that JUnit 4 and its eclipse plugin works faster and nicer. So I&#39;ve
&gt; decided change all my unit tests to JUnit.
&gt;
&gt; I have a runUnitTests ant target that is used to run (previously) the
&gt; test-ng tests that are marked as &quot;UnitTests&quot;
&gt;
&gt; As a start, I have changed this ant target to run all tests in my tests
&gt; target directory (i.e. using **/*.class)
&gt;
&gt; What I thought would happen was that JUnit would look at these classes, find
&gt; the ones that are marked with the JUnit 4 @Test annotation and run them.
&gt;
&gt; What I&#39;m finding however is that it is attempting to run EVERY class in that
&gt; folder as a test and they are either Test-NG tests or just other utility
&gt; classes. As a result, JUnit is throwing errors
&gt;
&gt; e.g.
&gt; Running au.tributech.tuxedo.beans.entity.PermissionTest$1
&gt;     [junit] Tests run: 2, Failures: 0, Errors: 2, Time elapsed: 0.017 sec
&gt;     [junit] Test au.tributech.tuxedo.beans.entity.PermissionTest$1 FAILED
&gt;     [junit] Running
&gt; au.tributech.tuxedo.beans.entity.PermissionTest$PermissionDescendant
&gt;     [junit] Tests run: 2, Failures: 0, Errors: 2, Time elapsed: 0.018 sec
&gt;     [junit] Test
&gt; au.tributech.tuxedo.beans.entity.PermissionTest$PermissionDescendant FAILED
&gt;
&gt; Is there any way out of the box to make Junit just run the tests that use
&gt; org.junit.Test annoations ??
&gt;
&gt; What I have got working (but its slow) is to write a custom ANT selector.
&gt; &lt;batchtest fork=&quot;yes&quot; todir=&quot;${test.report.dir}&quot;&gt;
&gt;   &lt;fileset dir=&quot;${test.fixtures.dir}&quot; includes=&quot;**/*.class&quot;&gt;
&gt;     &lt;custom classname=&quot;au.tributech.ant.JUnit4Selector&quot;
&gt; classpathref=&quot;project.test.run.classpath&quot;/&gt;
&gt;   &lt;/fileset&gt;
&gt; &lt;/batchtest&gt;
&gt;
&gt; The JUnit4Selector class I wrote simply reads in each file processed and
&gt; uses ASM-3.0 to look for JUnit4 annotations (@Test, @RunsWith etc..). If
&gt; they exist it processes that file otherwise skips it.
&gt;
&gt; This works but it is pretty slow and I can see it being painfully slow when
&gt; there are hundreds of unit tests.
&gt;
&gt; Surely I&#39;m missing something here and JUnit&#39;s ANT task is smarter than what
&gt; it is appearing. I don&#39;t want to have to specify EVERY unit test when I add
&gt; them. That is just a maintenance nightmare.
&gt;
&gt; Thanks for any pointers
&gt; --
